  "signature": "ed25519:b2e4a1c3d5f7e9b0c2d4f6a8b0c2e4f6a8b0d2e4f6c8a0b2d4f6e8a0c2d4f6",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA procedures documented in accordance with FDA 21 CFR Part 820 and ISO 9001. Version-controlled solver with documented release testing. Gradation 2 requires documented SQA plan and configuration management for the CFD solver.",
      "rationale": "The ANSYS Fluent solver version 2022 R2 is deployed under a documented SQA plan consistent with FDA guidance on software validation. Configuration management records confirm the specific solver binary used for all production runs. Regression test suite results are archived and traceable to the solver release. At MRL 2, Gradation 2 SQA is required and has been demonstrated."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Verification against at least one analytical or manufactured solution relevant to internal viscous flow. Gradation 2 requires documented code verification activity with quantified error norms.",
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed using the method of manufactured solutions for laminar pipe flow and lid-driven cavity benchmarks. L2 error norms confirm second-order spatial accuracy consistent with the solver's documented discretization scheme. Results are archived in the project verification report."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Richardson extrapolation or GCI analysis across at least three mesh refinement levels. Gradation 2 requires documented mesh sensitivity study; Gradation 3 additionally requires quantified discretization uncertainty estimate reported with QoI.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted using the Grid Convergence Index (GCI) methodology per Celik et al. (2008). The finest mesh (12.4 M cells) yields a GCI of 1.8% for the area-averaged wall shear stress, the primary hemolysis-driving QoI. The achieved level of 3 exceeds the MRL 2 requirement of 2, providing additional confidence in spatial accuracy."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions documented and traceable to calibrated instrumentation. Gradation 2 requires that flow rate, rotational speed, and fluid properties are measured and reported with uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted at the FDA CDRH flow laboratory. Flow rate was measured with a calibrated Coriolis meter (±0.5%), rotational speed with an optical tachometer (±0.1%), and fluid temperature with a calibrated RTD (±0.2°C). All instruments were within calibration at the time of testing. Boundary conditions applied to the CFD model are directly traceable to these measurements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric defined a priori. Gradation 2 requires documented comparison of model output to experimental QoI with reported agreement metric.",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) predicted by the CFD model was compared to experimentally measured NIH values at all five operating points. Agreement was assessed using the validation metric of Oberkampf and Trucano. Mean absolute percentage error across operating points was 11.3%, within the pre-specified 15% threshold documented in the validation plan."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI used in validation is the same as or directly maps to the COU QoI. Gradation 2 requires documented justification of QoI relevance.",
      "rationale": "The validation QoI (NIH, normalized index of hemolysis) is identical to the COU QoI. The relative hemolysis index RH is derived directly from NIH values at the device under test and the predicate device. No QoI transformation or surrogate mapping is required, eliminating a potential source of relevance uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "The validation activities were conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry — the same geometry class as the device under assessment — operating within the clinical CPB flow range of 3–6 L/min at rotational speeds of 2000–3500 RPM. The working fluid was a porcine blood analog with matched viscosity and density. The operating envelope of the validation experiments fully encompasses the five flow-speed combinations specified in the COU. Boundary condition fidelity, geometric similarity, and fluid property matching collectively establish that the validation activities are directly relevant to the intended COU without requiring extrapolation beyond the validated regime. The hemolysis power-law damage model (Giersiepen et al.) applied in the CFD solver has been validated specifically for centrifugal pump geometries in the peer-reviewed literature, and the validation dataset used here is drawn from the same experimental programme that underpins those published assessments. Furthermore, the FDA pump geometry serves as the community reference standard for computational hemolysis assessment, and its use here ensures that the validation evidence base is maximally relevant to regulatory decision-making for Class II CPB devices. No adjustment factors or relevance corrections are required; the validation scenario and the COU are sufficiently congruent that the validation evidence can be applied directly to support the credibility claim at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2 per ASME V&V 40 Table 1 guidance. Gradation 1 (awareness) is the required level; no formal assessment activity is mandated.",
      "rationale": "At Model Risk Level 2, ASME V&V 40 Table 1 indicates that Gradation 1 (awareness of the factor) is sufficient for numerical solver error. The team is aware that iterative convergence errors and floating-point round-off contribute to total numerical error; these are bounded by the discretization error analysis documented under the Discretization Error factor. No additional formal assessment is required at this MRL."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2. Gradation 1 requires only that the factor is identified and acknowledged in the credibility assessment.",
      "rationale": "Use error (operator error in model setup, boundary condition assignment, or post-processing) is acknowledged as a potential source of credibility risk. At MRL 2, Gradation 1 awareness is sufficient. Procedural controls including peer review of model setup and independent verification of post-processing scripts provide informal mitigation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Justification that the selected turbulence and hemolysis damage models are appropriate for the flow regime and QoI. Gradation 2 requires documented model selection rationale with reference to published validation evidence.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-omega turbulence model was selected based on its documented performance for rotating internal flows with adverse pressure gradients, consistent with published benchmarks for centrifugal pump hemolysis simulations. The Giersiepen power-law hemolysis damage model was selected as the community standard for this application class. Model selection rationale is documented in the modelling assumptions report."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Key model inputs (geometry, fluid properties, boundary conditions) documented with sources and uncertainty estimates. Gradation 2 requires that input uncertainty is characterised and its effect on QoI is qualitatively assessed.",
      "rationale": "Pump geometry was digitised from FDA-published CAD files with dimensional verification against physical measurements (±0.05 mm). Blood analog properties (density, viscosity) were measured at 37°C with calibrated instrumentation. A qualitative sensitivity analysis confirmed that ±5% variation in viscosity produces less than 3% change in NIH, supporting the adequacy of the input characterisation at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2. Gradation 1 awareness is sufficient; no formal sample characterisation activity is required.",
      "rationale": "Test samples (blood analog fluid batches) are acknowledged as a potential source of experimental variability. At MRL 2, Gradation 1 is sufficient. Fluid properties were measured per batch and are documented in the experimental records."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2. Gradation 1 awareness is sufficient; the team acknowledges that input parameters in the validation scenario may differ from COU parameters and has qualitatively confirmed they are within acceptable bounds.",
      "rationale": "The equivalency of input parameters between the validation scenario and the COU has been qualitatively reviewed. Operating conditions in the validation experiments span the COU operating envelope. No significant parameter mismatches requiring formal equivalency assessment have been identified at MRL 2."
    }
  ],
